## What we set out to do

Stage 8 of the KPU SKU + ProcessNode + CoolingSolution plan was reserved as
"floorplanner + visualization + geometric constraint validators (KPU
checkerboard pitch-match)" -- the open item that Stage 8a-b was meant to
deliver. The session began with the user's terse "proceed to the floorplanner,
visualization, and geometric constraint validator", and unfolded across three
arcs of design correction:

1. **Stage 8a -- circuit-class floorplanner** (initial cut). Bin silicon_bin
   blocks by silicon library (HP_LOGIC / SRAM / ANALOG / IO), derive a per-
   tile-class pitch, lay out the mesh with a single unified pitch (= max
   class pitch), surround with PHY strip + IO ring. Three GEOMETRY
   validators landed: `floorplan_pitch_match`,
   `floorplan_within_die_envelope`, `floorplan_aspect_ratio`. Tests covered
   structural invariants + CLI smoke. Pushed as the first commit on the
   branch.

2. **Stage 8b -- architectural-role view + what-if** (user redirect). User
   pointed out the circuit-class glyph table wasn't useful for design review
   -- they wanted to see compute tile (PE+L1+L2) vs memory tile (L3) sizes
   *as roles*, with whitespace per class, plus a what-if "die size if every
   compute tile were class X" comparison so the cost of mixing tile classes
   is visible. We added the architectural-role floorplan as a sibling
   derivation (same silicon_bin, different binning), made it the new CLI
   default, and added two more GEOMETRY validators:
   `floorplan_compute_memory_pitch_match` (the primary KPU checkerboard
   concern) and `floorplan_whitespace_fraction` (top-level die-efficiency
   alarm with what-if reference in the message).

3. **Stage 8b corrections -- checkerboard + memory subsystem + rendering**
   (user caught three concrete issues across two rounds):

   - First correction: the v1 checkerboard was column-pair `[CM][CM]` --
     each compute tile had only ONE memory neighbour. The user wanted true
     2D where every interior compute has 4 memory neighbours. Also the
     memory controllers were N=4 default square chunks scaled to mesh size,
     while real silicon has rectangular MCs sized by I/O bump pitch with
     count = `memory.memory_controllers` (T256 = 16 LPDDR ch, T768 = 8 HBM
     stacks). Per-channel area + aspect ratio became memory-type-driven.
     DRAM channels were drawn outside the die boundary, paired 1:1 with
     their MCs. Die expands when I/O perimeter requires more edge length
     than the mesh provides; corners reserved for vertical MCs to avoid
     horizontal/vertical overlap.

   - Second correction: rendering bugs visible in T128 -- some tiles
     rendered as 3 visual rows where others were 2 (rasterizer rounding
     mismatch); the IO ring disappeared (thickness scaled below one ASCII
     cell); control logic overlapped the corner mesh tile. Fixed: floor-
     consistent rasterization, fixed IO ring thickness, control moved to
     corner gap outside mesh.

The session ran through to merge in three substantive rounds plus a CodeRabbit
+ lint resolution round. PR #152 went green and merged as `48cb7e7`.

## Architectural decisions

### Two complementary floorplan views (circuit-class + architectural-role)

The key cross-cutting decision was to keep BOTH binnings of the same
`silicon_bin` rather than picking one. The circuit-class view answers "what
silicon library was built" (helpful for foundry / library reviews); the
architectural view answers "what does what" (helpful for architecture review
+ pitch-match validation). Both share the same per-tile area derivation
helpers; the divergence is in role-vs-library binning, layout strategy
(unified mesh vs true 2D checkerboard with separate MC subsystem), and
ASCII glyph map.

`cli/show_floorplan.py` defaults to the architectural view because that's
what the user reaches for first when reviewing a SKU. `--view circuit` falls
back to 8a. Captured as `DECISION-2026-05-10-001.yaml`.

### Memory controllers sized by memory type + I/O width, not by mesh size

The v1 implementation collapsed all PHY blocks into N=4 square chunks of
size `sqrt(total_phy_area / 4)`. The user noted this is wrong -- real silicon
MCs are rectangular (matching the I/O bump pattern), have count =
`memory.memory_controllers` (the SKU schema already exposes this), and are
sized per-channel by memory type (LPDDR PHYs are long narrow stripes, HBM
PHYs are squarer microbump arrays). We added `_PER_CHANNEL_PHY_AREA_MM2` and
`_PHY_ASPECT_RATIO` lookup tables keyed on memory type (lpddr5, hbm3, etc.),
with realistic per-channel area heuristics derived from published PHY-area
data for current-gen ~16nm logic. Refinement against PDK data is a Stage 8c
follow-up.

The die now expands when the I/O perimeter (channels x long_dim) requires
more edge length than the mesh provides -- preserving the invariant that
"MC area is independent of mesh size; channel count + width drive die
geometry." Mesh sits centred with whitespace gaps when extra_x / extra_y
> 0. Corners reserved for vertical (left/right) MCs so horizontal /
vertical MCs don't visually overlap.

### True 2D checkerboard, not column-pair

Initial implementation laid compute and memory in column pairs (`[C M] [C M]
...`) -- each compute had ONE memory neighbour to its right. User corrected
this: KPU's M0.5 checkerboard puts memory on N/S/E/W of every interior
compute (and vice versa). Switched to true 2D pattern: physical mesh =
`mesh_rows x (2 * mesh_cols)`, COMPUTE at `(r+c) % 2 == 0`, else MEMORY.
Locked in by `test_arch_true_2d_checkerboard_interior_compute_has_4_memory_neighbours`.

### Stage 8 stance: WARN-max thresholds during heuristic-v1

All 5 GEOMETRY validators have ERROR thresholds set deliberately high
(`_PITCH_RATIO_ERROR = 5.0x`, `_DIE_AREA_RATIO_ERROR = 3.0x`,
`_WHITESPACE_FRACTION_ERROR = 0.80`) so all 4 catalog SKUs land at WARN-max
and the Phase 6 catalog CI gate stays green. The findings still surface
real signal (T768's 3.59x compute/memory pitch mismatch, T64/T128's 1.87x
floorplan-vs-declared-die mismatch, ~76% architectural whitespace across
the catalog) -- the calibration to ERROR-level is Stage 8c work after
measured-silicon calibration.

